

<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="Ch1Sec2DefVectorSpace">
  <title>Definition of an abstract vector space</title>
  <p>
    Mathematics is about identifying patterns.
    We have found three different sets,
    <m>A</m>, <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>,
    which look very different on the surface
    but have much in common.
    In each set, there is an addition operation,
    a zero vector, and a scalar multiplication operation.
    Moreover, in each set, these operations satisfy the same rules.
    Let us now record this pattern by giving it a name
    and writing down the rules explicitly.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="real_vec_space">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>vector space</term> is a set <m>V</m>
        equipped with the following data:

        <dl>
          <li xml:id="D1">
            <title>D1.</title>
            <p>
              An <em>addition operation</em>.
              (That is, for every pair of elements <m>\ve{u}, \ve{v} \in V</m>,
              a new element <m>\ve{u} + \ve{v} \in V</m> is defined.)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="D2">
            <title>D2.</title>
            <p>
              A <em>zero vector</em>.
              (That is, a special vector 
              <m>\ve{0} \in V</m>
               is marked out.)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="D3">
            <title>D3.</title>
            <p>
              A <em>scalar multiplication operation</em>.
              (That is, for each real number <m>k</m>
              and each element <m>\ve{v} \in V</m>,
              a new element <m>k \smul\ve{v} \in V</m> is defined).
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </p>
<!-- TO DO: Make all references to the rules in this section into xrefs -->

      <p>
        This data should satisfy
        the following rules for all
         <m>\ve{u}, \ve{v}, \ve{w}</m> in <m>V</m>
        and for all real numbers <m>k</m> and <m>l</m>:
      </p>

        <dl>
          <li xml:id="R1">
            <title>R1.</title>
            <p>
              <m>\ve{v} + \ve{w} = \ve{w} + \ve{v}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R2">
            <title>R2.</title>
            <p>
              <m>(\ve{u} + \ve{v}) + \ve{w} = \ve{u} + (\ve{v} + \ve{w})</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R3a">
            <title>R3a.</title>
            <p>
              <m>\ve{0} + \ve{v} = \ve{v}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R3b">
            <title>R3b.</title>
            <p> <m>\ve{v} + \ve{0} = \ve{v}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R4">
            <title>R4.</title>
            <p>
              <m>k \smul(\ve{v} + \ve{w}) = k \smul\ve{v} + k \smul\ve{w}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R5">
            <title>R5.</title>
            <p>
              <m>(k + l) \smul\ve{v} = k \smul\ve{v} + l \smul{\ve{v}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R6">
            <title>R6.</title>
            <p>
              <m>k \smul(l \smul\ve{v}) = (kl) \smul\ve{v}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R7">
            <title>R7.</title>
            <p>
              <m>1 \smul\ve{v} = \ve{v}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="R8">
            <title>R8.</title>
            <p>
              <m>0 \smul\ve{v} = \ve{0}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    We will call the elements of a vector space <term>vectors</term>,
    and we will write them in boldface eg.
    <m>\ve{v} \in V</m>.
    We do this to distinguish vectors from real numbers,
    which we will call <em>scalars</em>,
    and which don't have a boldface.
    It is difficult to use boldface in handwriting,
    so you can write them with an arrow on top, like
    <m>\vec{v}</m>,
    or underline them, like <m>\underline{v}</m>.
    It is not essential to do this,
    because it is usually clear from the context.
    But it may help you to think more clearly about their difference.
  </p>

  <p>
    In this chapter we will write scalar multiplication with
    a <m>\cdot</m>, for instance <m>k \cdot\ve{v}</m>,
    but in later chapters we will simply write it as
    <m>k \ve{v}</m> for brevity, so be careful!
  </p>

  <p>
    To prove that a certain set can be
    given the structure of a vector space,
    one therefore needs to do the following:
  </p>

  <assemblage>
    <p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Define a set <m>V</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Define the data of
          an addition operation (D1),
          a zero vector (D2), and a
          scalar multiplication operation (D3)
          on <m>V</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Check that this data satisfies the rules (R1) &ndash; (R8).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  </assemblage>
</section>

